: "343K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "ferrous iron (Fe2+)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic hydrothermal water; Fe2+-promoted retro-aldol cleavage"}, "mechanism": "Fe2+-catalyzed retro-aldol cleavage of isocitrate yields the C2 aldehydo-acid glyoxylate and the C4 dicarboxylate succinate.", "reasoning": "This reaction directly follows the experimentally demonstrated iron-promoted network in which isocitrate is cleaved to glyoxylate and succinate at 70\u00b0C in water (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019). Mackinawite is included as a hydrothermal Fe-S mineral agent to satisfy network mineral specification while remaining compatible with anoxic vent settings."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "UV dehydration of glyoxylic acid hydrate to glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_001"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV photoredox with TiO2-supported surface exposure", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV-irradiated surface pools; dehydration of gem-diol form"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical dehydration of the gem-diol/hydrate regenerates the aldehyde functionality of glyoxylate with loss of water.", "reasoning": "The curated literature specifically identifies UV-driven conversion of 2,2-dihydroxyacetic acid to glyoxylate in surface pools (Liu et al., 2021). TiO2 is included as an allowed surface photocatalytic mineral agent consistent with UV photochemistry, though the key evidential basis is the photoredox chemistry reported by Liu, Wu, Kufner, Sasselov, Fischer & Sutherland (2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Iron-promoted reductive amination of glyoxylate to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "ferrous iron (Fe2+)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "elemental iron (Fe0), ferrous iron (Fe2+)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic hydrothermal water; mild hydrothermal conditions"}, "mechanism": "Hydroxylamine acts as nitrogen donor and iron provides reducing equivalents to convert the alpha-keto acid glyoxylate into the amino acid glycine.", "reasoning": "This is the experimentally supported upstream route from glyoxylate to glycine under iron-promoted hydrothermal conditions at 70\u00b0C in water (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2019). It is one of the key documented routes feeding serine synthesis via glycine."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-310K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted aqueous hydrolysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "cyanosulfidic surface pools; ambient aqueous hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Sequential hydration of the nitrile carbon forms an amide intermediate and then the carboxylic acid glycine with release of ammonia.", "reasoning": "The serine literature review identifies aminoacetonitrile hydrolysis to glycine under ambient aqueous cyanosulfidic conditions as part of the Patel et al. framework (Patel et al., 2015). Montmorillonite and phosphate minerals are included as permissible surface mineral agents for concentration and hydrolytic cycling in evaporitic pools."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Hydrothermal amination of peracetic acid to glycine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS2), elemental iron (Fe0)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "submarine hydrothermal conditions; elevated temperature"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia attacks the oxidized acetyl/peroxyacetyl ce